Exploratory analysis: Substantive procedures

This exploratory analysis focuses on the Substantive procedures dimension and includes various data summaries in table and graphical forms. The dimension is concpetualised as Political vs.Legal.

List of items

The Substantive Procedures scale has been constructed on the basis of these items:

Item Question
24 Is there a substantive admissibility check?
25 Who decides about the substantive admissibility?
26 Is there a legal remedy against the decision on substantive admissibility?
27 Who decides about the claim for remedy in the substantive admissibility procedure?
28 Who can initiate the substantive remedy procedure (state actor - initiator - anyone)?
29 Does the substantive admissibility procedure take place before the signature collection?
31 Do participants have a right to be heard in the substantive admissibility procedure?
32 Is there an evidentiary procedure in the substantive admissibility procedure?
33 Are the legal consequences of the substantive admissibility procedure binding?
34 Is invalidity the legal consequence of substantive inadmissibility?

Checking data

There are two important points:

    1. Substantive procedures does not apply to the Law-Initiated instrument.
    1. Item 29 (on checks before signature collection) does not apply to Executive, Legislature & Subnational. In this analysis this item is removed so we can make better comparisons.

Distribution of items Legal vs.Political

The main take home point here is that item 32 seems redundant virtually no Legal cases; perhaps items 31 and 25 should be considered as well. Remember having many items with low counts reduced the variance, and the possibility of getting higher values on the Legal dimension.

Country check

Another aspect worth checking is the Country impact. The visualisation below allows us to check how Country affects substantive prohibitions. It is organised by the items on Y axis and the Countries on the X axis. The bubble represent the count (i.e., how many prohibitions a country has per item). This is related to the number of instruments a country has; thus a country with 5, will have a maximum number of 5 prohibitions.

Visualising these country effects allows us to see whether a particular country is driving the count for a particular Item.

Matrix of Legal value counts for each item organised by country
